  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world, including China. \n\nMoney laundering involves the process of making illegally obtained money appear legitimate by concealing its true origin. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions or manipulations of financial systems. Because it facilitates criminal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, and terrorism financing, money laundering is considered a serious criminal offense globally.\n\nIn China, the government has established stringent laws and regulations to combat money laundering. The **Anti-Money Laundering Law of the People's Republic of China** (2007) explicitly defines money laundering as a crime and outlines the legal responsibilities for individuals and institutions involved in such activities. Financial institutions are required to implement thorough anti-money laundering (AML) measures, including customer identification, record-keeping, and reporting suspicious transactions.\n\nInternational cooperation also plays a significant role in combating money laundering, with China actively participating in global efforts and adhering to standards set by organizations like the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is illegal, and those found guilty of it can face severe legal penalties, including fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture.",
